problem:
In the diagram, the length of $DC$ is twice the length of $BD.$ What is the area of the triangle $ABC?$ [asy]
draw((0,0)--(-3,0)--(0,4)--cycle);
draw((0,0)--(6,0)--(0,4)--cycle);
label("3",(-1.5,0),N);
label("4",(0,2),E);
label("$A$",(0,4),N);
label("$B$",(-3,0),S);
label("$C$",(6,0),S);
label("$D$",(0,0),S);
draw((0,0.4)--(0.4,0.4)--(0.4,0));
[/asy]

solution:
Since $BD=3$ and $DC$ is twice the length of $BD,$ then $DC=6.$ [asy]
draw((0,0)--(-3,0)--(0,4)--cycle);
draw((0,0)--(6,0)--(0,4)--cycle);
label("3",(-1.5,0),N);
label("4",(0,2),E);
label("$A$",(0,4),N);
label("$B$",(-3,0),S);
label("$C$",(6,0),S);
label("$D$",(0,0),S);
label("6",(3,0),N);
draw((0,0.4)--(0.4,0.4)--(0.4,0));
[/asy] Therefore, triangle $ABC$ has a base of length $9$ and a height of length $4.$ Thus, the area of triangle $ABC$ is $$\frac{1}{2}bh = \frac{1}{2}(9)(4) = \frac{1}{2}(36) = \boxed{18}.$$

